  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In January 2019, a team of researchers at the University of Louisville published a paper in <em>Science Advances</em> that should have detonated across medicine like a grenade. It didn't. The paper, led by Stephen Dominy and Casey Lynch, reported that <em>Porphyromonas gingivalis</em> — a gram-negative anaerobe most people have never heard of, the primary pathogen behind the gum disease most people ignore — was present in 96% of the Alzheimer's brain samples they examined. Not statistically associated with. Not correlated in a population study. Present in. Physically. Its DNA, its proteins, its signature enzymes — inside the brains of people who died with Alzheimer's disease.</p>
  <p>The company formed to turn this finding into a drug, Cortexyme, raised $146 million in venture and public capital. It ran a Phase 2/3 clinical trial of a gingipain inhibitor called atuzaginstat. In 2021, the trial was placed on partial clinical hold by the FDA after liver toxicity signals emerged. The company subsequently collapsed, rebranding and restructuring as it burned through its runway. The drug didn't work — or at least, didn't work well enough, safely enough, to matter.</p>
  <p>That gap — between a finding that looks, on its face, like one of the most important discoveries in neuroscience in a generation, and a clinical program that quietly fell apart — is not a reason to dismiss the science. It is the entire story. Because the science, stripped of the venture capital narrative and the breathless press releases, remains genuinely strange and genuinely important. And the institutional failure it exposes — medicine's century-long habit of treating the mouth as a separate country — is not resolved by a failed drug trial.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-gingipains-actually-do" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Gingipains Actually Do</h2>
  <p>The reason the 2019 <em>Science Advances</em> paper generated the response it did is mechanistic specificity. This is not a story about inflammation in general. It is not a story about oral bacteria being vaguely bad for you in ways that compound over decades. It is a story about a specific set of enzymes doing a specific thing to specific proteins that define a specific disease.</p>
  <p><em>P. gingivalis</em> produces cysteine proteases called gingipains — arginine-specific (RgpA, RgpB) and lysine-specific (Kgp) variants — that function as the bacterium's primary virulence machinery. They degrade host immune proteins, cleave complement components, and allow the organism to evade clearance with unusual efficiency. In the context of Alzheimer's disease, what matters is what they do to tau and amyloid precursor protein. The Dominy et al. study found that gingipain levels in brain tissue correlated directly with tau pathology and with markers of neurodegeneration, including ubiquitin. The proteases cleave tau in patterns consistent with the neurofibrillary tangle formation that defines Alzheimer's histology.</p>
  <p>This is not correlation. This is a plausible molecular mechanism. The distinction matters enormously, because most of the epidemiological literature linking oral health to systemic disease operates at the level of association — people with gum disease have more heart attacks, more adverse pregnancy outcomes, more cognitive decline. Confounders abound. Smoking, diabetes, socioeconomic status, and healthcare access all track with periodontal disease and independently predict every one of those outcomes. Disentangling the signal from the noise in observational data is genuinely hard.</p>
  <p>Gingipains in brain tissue are different. They are not a statistical association. They are a physical finding with a characterized biochemical activity. The question is whether that activity is causally upstream of Alzheimer's pathology, downstream of it, or incidental to a brain that has already been compromised by other mechanisms. That question remains open. But it is a more interesting and more tractable question than most of what passes for Alzheimer's research.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Gingipain levels in brain tissue correlated directly with tau pathology. This is not correlation. This is a plausible molecular mechanism. The distinction matters enormously."</p></aside>

<section id="the-cortexyme-collapse" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Cortexyme Collapse, Reported Honestly</h2>
  <p>Cortexyme's atuzaginstat was a small-molecule inhibitor designed to block gingipain activity in the brain. The hypothesis was clean: if gingipains are cleaving tau and driving neurodegeneration, inhibit the gingipains, slow the disease. The company's Phase 2/3 GAIN trial enrolled 643 participants with mild-to-moderate Alzheimer's disease. In October 2021, the FDA placed the trial on partial clinical hold after elevated liver enzymes were observed in a subset of patients. The trial was subsequently terminated.</p>
  <p>The efficacy data that emerged before termination was, at best, mixed. Some secondary endpoints showed signals in a subgroup of patients with high baseline gingipain levels. The company leaned hard on those subgroup analyses in its communications. Investors and science journalists who wanted a breakthrough leaned with them. This is a familiar pattern in Alzheimer's drug development — a field that has produced more Phase 3 failures than any other therapeutic area, with over 99% of trials failing between 2002 and 2012 according to a review by Cummings et al. in <em>Alzheimer's Research and Therapy</em> (2014).</p>
  <p>What the Cortexyme failure tells us is not that <em>P. gingivalis</em> is irrelevant to Alzheimer's disease. It tells us that detecting a bacterium in brain tissue is not the same as proving it causes disease, and that proving it causes disease is not the same as being able to drug the mechanism safely. These are three separate evidentiary bars, and the field cleared only the first one. The second bar — independent replication of the brain tissue findings at scale — has not been cleared. The 2019 study examined a relatively small number of samples, and while the detection rate was striking, the finding has not been reproduced in a large, independent, pre-registered study. That absence is not exculpatory for <em>P. gingivalis</em>, but it is a reason for precision about what we know.</p>
</section>

