<section id="the-cardiovascular-case" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Cardiovascular Case, Which Is Stronger</h2>
  <p>The Alzheimer's angle is the stranger story, but the cardiovascular evidence is the more replicated one, and it deserves equal weight. A 2025 systematic review in <em>Oral Diseases</em> — surveying the bidirectional relationships between oral dysbiosis and systemic disease — confirmed that the mechanistic pathways linking periodontal pathogens to cardiovascular disease are now independently characterized across multiple research groups and multiple biological levels.</p>
  <p>The primary mechanism runs through lipopolysaccharide. <em>P. gingivalis</em> and other gram-negative periodontal pathogens shed LPS continuously. During chewing, toothbrushing, and dental procedures — and chronically through the ulcerated epithelium of inflamed gingival tissue — these organisms and their products enter systemic circulation. LPS binds Toll-like receptor 4 on vascular endothelial cells, triggering NF-κB activation, upregulation of adhesion molecules, and the inflammatory cascade that drives foam cell formation and atherosclerotic plaque development. This is not a hypothesis. TLR4-mediated endothelial activation is one of the best-characterized pathways in vascular biology.</p>
  <p><em>P. gingivalis</em> itself has been cultured from human atherosclerotic plaques. A study by Haraszthy et al. published in the <em>Journal of Periodontology</em> (2000) detected periodontal pathogens including <em>P. gingivalis</em> in 30% of carotid endarterectomy specimens. Subsequent work has found bacterial DNA from oral species in coronary artery plaques with enough consistency that the finding is no longer considered anomalous — it is considered a starting point for mechanistic investigation.</p>
  <p>The population-level data is consistent with this. Meta-analyses — including a comprehensive analysis by Bahekar et al. in the <em>American Heart Journal</em> (2007), covering over 1 million subjects — have found that periodontitis is associated with approximately a 2.7-fold increase in cardiovascular disease risk after adjustment for traditional risk factors. The confounding problem is real and should not be minimized: people with severe gum disease are more likely to smoke, more likely to have diabetes, and less likely to have consistent access to healthcare. But the association persists after adjustment in the better-controlled analyses, and the biological mechanism is independently plausible.</p>
  <p>The critical evidentiary gap is intervention data. Treating periodontal disease has not been shown in large randomized controlled trials to meaningfully reduce cardiovascular events. The PERIODONT trial and related intervention studies have generally found that periodontal treatment improves surrogate markers — C-reactive protein, endothelial function measures, interleukin-6 levels — without producing statistically significant reductions in hard cardiovascular endpoints. This is either because the effect size is real but modest and requires larger trials to detect, or because the association is driven by confounders that treatment cannot address, or because the causal pathway is more complex than the simple model suggests. All three possibilities remain live.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"<em>P. gingivalis</em> has been cultured from human atherosclerotic plaques. The finding is no longer considered anomalous — it is considered a starting point for mechanistic investigation."</p></aside>

<section id="beyond-the-brain-and-heart" class="reveal">
  <h2>Beyond the Brain and Heart</h2>
  <p>The systemic reach of oral dysbiosis extends further than the two headline conditions. The adverse pregnancy outcome data is, in some ways, the most alarming in terms of raw effect size. Cohort studies have found periodontal disease associated with a sevenfold increased risk of preterm birth in some populations, a finding that has been replicated across multiple countries and ethnic groups. The mechanism is plausible — systemic LPS exposure and elevated prostaglandin E2 from periodontal inflammation can trigger premature uterine contractions — and <em>P. gingivalis</em> has been detected in placental tissue from adverse pregnancy outcomes.</p>
  <p>A 2010 study by Offenbacher et al. in the <em>American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology</em> found oral bacteria, including <em>P. gingivalis</em>, in the amniotic fluid and placental membranes of women who delivered preterm. The hematogenous route — bacteria traveling from inflamed gingival tissue through the bloodstream to the placenta — is biologically coherent. Whether treating periodontitis during pregnancy reduces preterm birth rates has been tested in RCTs with inconsistent results, mirroring the cardiovascular intervention literature.</p>
  <p>The diabetes relationship is bidirectional in a way that makes causal inference particularly difficult. Hyperglycemia impairs neutrophil function and promotes the growth of periodontal pathogens; periodontal inflammation worsens insulin resistance through cytokine-mediated mechanisms. The 2025 <em>Oral Diseases</em> systematic review characterized this as a confirmed bidirectional relationship, with each condition amplifying the other through independent pathways. For a disease affecting 37 million Americans, the clinical implications of that bidirectionality are not trivial.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-confounding-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Confounding Problem Deserves More Than a Token Paragraph</h2>
  <p>The counter-argument to this entire body of literature is not frivolous, and it should not be treated as a speed bump on the way to a predetermined conclusion. Periodontal disease is not randomly distributed in the population. It tracks with smoking, with poorly controlled diabetes, with low socioeconomic status, with limited healthcare access, and with a cluster of behavioral and environmental factors that independently predict cardiovascular disease, cognitive decline, and adverse pregnancy outcomes. The question of whether periodontal disease is a cause of these outcomes, a co-occurring condition driven by shared upstream factors, or a marker of the kind of systemic inflammation that produces all of them simultaneously — that question is genuinely unresolved.</p>
  <p>The 96% detection rate for <em>P. gingivalis</em> in Alzheimer's brain tissue is striking, but it requires independent replication in larger, more diverse samples with rigorous controls for post-mortem contamination and shared risk factors. The samples in the Dominy et al. study were not large by the standards of neuropathology research, and the study was conducted by researchers with a direct financial interest in the gingipain inhibitor hypothesis — a conflict of interest that does not invalidate the findings but does elevate the evidentiary bar for the replication standard.</p>
  <p>The intervention trial literature — the place where causal claims go to be tested — has not yet delivered the clean result that would settle the debate. Until a large, well-powered RCT shows that treating periodontal disease reduces incident Alzheimer's disease, cardiovascular events, or preterm birth in populations where confounders are rigorously controlled, the causal claim remains a hypothesis. A well-supported, mechanistically plausible, biologically coherent hypothesis — but a hypothesis.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The physician who manages your heart disease has almost certainly never asked about your gums. Your insurance treats the mouth as a separate body. This is not a scientific position. It is an institutional one."</p></aside>

<section id="the-institutional-absurdity" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Institutional Absurdity</h2>
  <p>Here is what is not a hypothesis: periodontal disease affects approximately 50% of American adults over 30, with severe periodontitis affecting roughly 8.9% of the adult population, according to data from the CDC's National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. It is largely preventable with consistent oral hygiene and regular professional care. It is associated — causally or not — with the leading causes of death and disability in the developed world. And it is managed in a parallel healthcare system that shares almost nothing with the physicians who manage those leading causes of death.</p>
  <p>Dental care in the United States is separately insured, separately trained, separately credentialed, and institutionally siloed from medicine in ways that have no scientific justification. The separation is historical and financial, not biological. The mouth is not a separate organ system. The gingival vasculature connects directly to systemic circulation. The bacteria that colonize periodontal pockets do not stop at the gum line. The inflammatory mediators produced in response to oral dysbiosis circulate. None of this is controversial among researchers. All of it is ignored by the insurance and institutional architecture that governs how care is actually delivered.</p>
  <p>A cardiologist managing a patient with established coronary artery disease will typically assess lipid panels, blood pressure, glycemic control, smoking status, physical activity, diet, sleep, and psychological stress. The question of whether that patient has severe periodontitis — a condition associated with a 2.7-fold increase in cardiovascular risk in meta-analyses, present in the coronary plaques of roughly 30% of patients undergoing endarterectomy — will almost certainly not be asked. Not because the cardiologist is negligent. Because the system was not built to ask it.</p>
  <p>Medicare, the primary insurer for the population at highest risk for both cardiovascular disease and Alzheimer's disease, provides essentially no dental coverage. The Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 added limited dental benefits for Medicare Advantage plans, but comprehensive periodontal care remains largely out of pocket for the elderly population most likely to benefit from it. Medicaid dental coverage for adults varies by state and is frequently inadequate. The practical consequence is that the patients most likely to have severe periodontitis are the patients least likely to receive treatment for it — and most likely to bear the systemic consequences, whatever those consequences ultimately prove to be.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Mechanistic Pathway: How Oral Bacteria May Reach Distant Tissues</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Entry point:</strong> Ulcerated gingival epithelium in inflamed periodontal tissue provides direct vascular access during chewing, brushing, and dental procedures</li>
    <li><strong>Immune evasion:</strong> <em>P. gingivalis</em> fimbriae and gingipains degrade complement proteins and neutrophil chemokines, enabling survival in circulation</li>
    <li><strong>Vascular pathway:</strong> LPS activates TLR4 on endothelial cells → NF-κB → adhesion molecule upregulation → foam cell formation → atherosclerotic plaque</li>
    <li><strong>Neural pathway (hypothesized):</strong> Hematogenous spread or retrograde transport via trigeminal nerve; gingipains cleave tau and APP in patterns consistent with Alzheimer's pathology</li>
    <li><strong>Placental pathway:</strong> Bacteremia during pregnancy; <em>P. gingivalis</em> detected in placental tissue and amniotic fluid from preterm deliveries</li>
    <li><strong>Replication status:</strong> Vascular mechanism well-characterized; neural mechanism detected but not independently replicated at scale; intervention trials have not yet confirmed hard endpoint reduction</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="where-the-science-actually-stands" class="reveal">
  <h2>Where the Science Actually Stands</h2>
  <p>The honest summary is this. A specific oral pathogen has been physically detected in the brains of Alzheimer's patients, in coronary artery plaques, and in placental tissue from adverse pregnancy outcomes. Its primary virulence enzymes have a characterized biochemical activity on the exact proteins that define Alzheimer's histology. The systemic inflammatory pathway by which it and related organisms damage vascular endothelium is independently well-characterized. The population-level associations between periodontal disease and cardiovascular disease, adverse pregnancy outcomes, and cognitive decline are consistent across multiple study designs and multiple populations.</p>
  <p>What the science cannot yet prove is causation. The intervention trials have not delivered. The replication of the brain tissue findings has not been completed at the scale required to treat the finding as established. The one drug company that tried to exploit the mechanistic finding raised $146 million and produced a hepatotoxic compound with mixed efficacy signals in a terminated trial. The gap between a plausible mechanism and a working drug is, as Alzheimer's researchers know better than anyone, vast.</p>
  <p>None of that changes what the 2025 <em>Oral Diseases</em> systematic review characterized as a confirmed bidirectional relationship between oral dysbiosis and multiple systemic conditions, with mechanistic pathways increasingly characterized. None of it changes the TLR4 endothelial activation data, which does not depend on the Cortexyme story at all. None of it changes the fact that <em>P. gingivalis</em> was found in 96% of examined Alzheimer's brain samples, a finding that demands rigorous independent investigation rather than either breathless endorsement or reflexive dismissal.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-institutional-question" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Question Medicine Has Not Answered</h2>
  <p>The science is unresolved. The institutional failure is not. If a bacterium that colonizes the mouths of half of all American adults is being found in the brains of Alzheimer's patients and in the walls of coronary arteries — if its enzymes can be shown to cleave the proteins that define the most expensive and most devastating neurodegenerative disease in the developed world — then the physician who manages your heart disease has almost certainly never asked about your gums. The specialist managing your cognitive decline has almost certainly never ordered a periodontal assessment. Your insurance treats the mouth as a separate body, not because the biology supports that separation, but because the institutional architecture was built that way, and nobody with sufficient power has found it worth the disruption to change it.</p>
  <p>That is not a scientific position. It is a financial and institutional one. And it is costing patients — in untreated periodontal disease that compounds silently for decades, in cardiovascular risk that goes unaddressed because no one thought to ask about the gums, in a research agenda that has been distorted by the venture capital logic of a single drug hypothesis rather than the slower, harder work of establishing causation through intervention trials.</p>
  <p>The mouth is not separate from the body. It never was. Medicine built a wall there for reasons that had nothing to do with anatomy, and the evidence accumulating on both sides of that wall is making the wall look increasingly indefensible. The science will eventually settle the causal questions. The institutional question — why we built the wall, who benefits from keeping it, and what it costs the patients on the other side — that one is answerable right now.</p>
</section>

